{
  "query": "What is the available evidence on the effectiveness of using nurse plants to improve grassland plant community composition and richness?",
  "relevant_summary": "The available evidence on nurse plants for improving grassland plant community composition and richness shows mixed and generally limited effectiveness. One replicated, controlled study in France found that sowing seeds of nurse plants reduced the similarity of the plant community to that of nearby intact steppe compared to areas where no seeds were sown (Action 3401). The same study found that sowing seeds of nurse plants did not change plant species richness and richness was lower than in nearby intact steppe (Action 3401). One replicated, controlled study in Slovenia found that sowing a seed mix containing nurse species resulted in a community composition that was less similar to the target community when compared to sowing a seed mix that did not contain nurse species (Action 3402). The Slovenia study also found that sowing a seed mix containing nurse species did not increase species richness compared to sowing a seed mix that did not contain nurse species (Action 3402). A replicated, paired, controlled study in the USA found that sowing seeds of nurse plants alongside that of grassland species did not change grass abundance or forb abundance (Action 3402). However, nurse plants showed some benefits for plant establishment: one replicated, controlled study in Spain found that sowing seeds under nurse plants increased seed germination (Action 3402). For survival outcomes, one of two replicated, controlled studies in Kenya and Spain found that sowing seeds or planting under nurse plants increased survival of planted plants, while the other study found that sowing seeds under nurse plants initially increased seedling survival, but there was no difference in survival after two to three years (Action 3402).",
