{
  "query": "To what extent does pre-seeding site preparation, such as removing vegetation or leaf litter, affect seed germination?",
  "relevant_summary": "Pre-seeding site preparation involving vegetation and leaf litter removal shows mixed effects on seed germination. Removing leaf litter before seeding/planting had mixed effects on the number of seedlings of sown plant species in two of three replicated, controlled studies in Germany, Belgium and Hungary, while one study found no change in the number of seedlings of either of two grass species (Action 3414). Vegetation removal before seeding showed positive effects in some cases, with one of two replicated, controlled studies in the UK and Belgium finding that removing vegetation before sowing seeds increased the germination rate of sown species, while the other study found that removing vegetation, along with removing leaf litter, before sowing seeds increased the number of seedlings for one of three species (Action 3416). In contrast, leaf litter removal in forest settings showed negative effects, with one replicated, controlled study in Costa Rica finding that leaf litter removal decreased the density of new tree seedlings (Action 1246). Soil surface disturbance in peatlands (without planting) led to colonization by wetland-characteristic plant species in two replicated, paired, controlled, before-and-after studies in Germany and Sweden, though the study in Germany noted that peat-forming species did not colonize the fen (Action 1811).",
