{"query": "What does the evidence from North America show about the impact of sowing grass seeds on native grass and forb abundance?", "summary": "Evidence from North America shows mixed effects of sowing grass seeds on native grass and forb abundance. For sowing native grass and forb seeds, twelve studies from North America were included in the research. Two of three replicated, randomized, controlled studies in the Czech Republic and the USA found that sowing native grass and forb seeds increased the cover of grass species, while one study found no change in grass cover (Action 3432). Three of four replicated, randomized, controlled studies found that sowing native grass and forb seeds increased the cover or density of forb species, with one study showing that forb cover increased one year after sowing but did not differ from unsown areas after 10 years (Action 3432). One study in the USA found that sowing native grass and forb seeds increased the cover of native plant species (Action 3432).

For sowing grass seeds generally, six studies were conducted in North America. Three of four replicated studies in the USA and Canada found that sowing grass seeds either reduced native grass cover or did not alter native grass density, while one study found that grass cover was higher after two years but showed no difference after seven years (Action 3397). One of two replicated studies found that sowing grass seeds reduced the abundance of native forb species, while the other study found no change in native forb density (Action 3397). One study in the USA found that sowing grass seeds did not alter the cover of native plant species (Action 3397).

Nine studies from North America examined adding fertilizer alongside seeding, with one study in the USA finding that adding fertilizer and sowing seeds increased the biomass of three native grass species (Action 3427).", "action_ids": ["3432","3397","3427"]}

