{
  "query": "How do the effects of grassland sowing interventions change over time, based on available evidence?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, the effects of grassland sowing interventions show distinct temporal patterns. In the short term (first year), sowing native grass and forb seeds increased plant species richness during the first year, but after 3-13 years, species richness did not differ between sown and unsown areas or was lower in sown areas (Action 3432). However, one study found that after one year, sowing did not alter plant species richness but after eight years, species richness was higher than in unsown areas (Action 3432). Over time, plant communities became more similar to those of intact grasslands (Action 3432). For forb species specifically, one study found that one year after sowing, the cover of forb species increased, but after 10 years it did not differ between sown and unsown areas (Action 3432). For overall vegetation abundance, one study found that sowing native grass and forb seeds increased plant species richness during the first 2-7 years, but after eight years, species richness did not differ between sown and unsown areas (Action 3432). In terms of restoration timelines, six studies saw positive signs of restoration in less than five years, 11 studies within 10 years and two studies found restoration took more than 10 years, while six studies found limited or slow changes in plant communities following restoration (Action 133). Two studies found differences in vegetation between restored and existing species-rich grasslands nine or 60 years after restoration (Action 133). For grasslands restored from arable land, butterfly communities developed to become increasingly similar to existing high-quality grasslands over the first 10 years after establishment (Action 3929), and species richness was higher on grasslands created less than 10 years ago than on grasslands created more than 20 years ago (Action 3929).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3432",
    "133",
    "3929"
  ]
}

