{
  "query": "In European grassland restoration, what are the benefits and drawbacks of sowing non-native grass seeds versus seeds from a local source?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence from grassland restoration studies, there are several documented benefits and drawbacks of different seed sourcing approaches:\n\nBenefits of local source seeds: One replicated, controlled study in Italy found that sowing grassland seeds from a local source increased plant species richness compared to sowing a commercial seed mix (Action 3400). A replicated, controlled study in Germany found that sowing grassland seeds from a local source, along with increasing the number of species in a seed mix, led to an increase in the species richness of target plants and increased cover of target plant species (Action 3400). One replicated study in the USA found that after sowing grassland seeds from a local source, vegetation cover increased over time compared to areas sown with non-native seeds (Action 3400).\n\nDrawbacks of local source seeds: The same USA study found that while vegetation cover increased with local seeds, the density of individual plants declined compared to non-native seeds (Action 3400). A replicated, randomized, controlled experiment in the USA found that sowing Sandberg bluegrass seeds from a local source did not change the survival of sown plants compared to sowing non-local varieties (Action 3400).\n\nNeutral outcomes: One replicated, controlled study in Germany found that vegetation cover did not differ between areas sown with local source seeds and those sown with commercial grass seed (Action 3400). Two replicated studies in the USA and Italy found that sowing grassland seeds from a local source did not alter vegetation height compared to sowing non-native grass seeds or a commercial seed mix (Action 3400).\n\nContext from native species studies: Studies examining native grass and forb seeding found that sixteen of 28 controlled studies in Europe, North America and New Zealand found that sowing native grass and forb seeds increased overall plant species richness, though seven studies found no change and three found initial increases followed by later declines (Action 3432). European studies showed that grasslands established by sowing grasses, legumes and forbs had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than grasslands established with grass-only mixes or less competitive species (Action 3929).",
